{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-topic-topic-tsx","path":"/topics/head-neck-cancers-recognition-referral/","result":{"data":{"firstChapter":{"id":"5a4e0ab7-b961-5ac5-acf5-588f3e0eb657","slug":"summary","fullItemName":"Summary","subChapters":[],"depth":1,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field e753a362-ec83-4bcb-99b4-61bd6648730f --><h1>Head and neck cancers - recognition and referral:Â Summary</h1><!-- end field e753a362-ec83-4bcb-99b4-61bd6648730f -->","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 35f5c36d-823e-45fb-a6e9-8faa517317ae --><!-- begin field fdfbbc09-6778-4d34-9a50-eda98b4694c4 --><ul><li>Laryngeal cancer<ul><li>Over 2000 new laryngeal cancers are diagnosed each year in the UK.</li><li>The 5 year survival is 70%.</li><li>The most common symptom is hoarseness, sometimes accompanied by throat pain.</li><li>Consider a suspected cancer pathway referral (for an appointment within 2 weeks) for laryngeal cancer in people aged 45 years and over with:<ul><li>Persistent unexplained hoarseness, or</li><li>An unexplained lump in the neck (new NICE recommendation for 2015).</li></ul></li></ul></li><li>Oral cancer<ul><li>Over 6500 new oral cancers are diagnosed each year in the UK.</li><li>It is seen in both sexes. Two-thirds of new diagnoses are in males.</li><li>Symptoms include persistent ulceration, a mass, or abnormal bleeding. It can present as advanced disease with regional lymphadenopathy.</li><li>Consider a suspected cancer pathway referral (for an appointment within 2 weeks) for oral cancer in people with either:<ul><li>Unexplained ulceration in the oral cavity lasting for more than 3 weeks, or</li><li>A persistent and unexplained lump in the neck (new NICE recommendation for 2015).</li></ul></li><li>Consider an urgent referral (for an appointment within 2 weeks) for assessment for possible oral cancer by a dentist in people who have either:<ul><li>A lump on the lip or in the oral cavity, or</li><li>A red or red and white patch in the oral cavity consistent with erythroplakia or erythroleukoplakia (new NICE recommendation for 2015).</li></ul></li><li>Consider a suspected cancer pathway referral by the dentist (for an appointment within 2 weeks) for oral cancer in people when assessed by a dentist as having either:<ul><li>A lump on the lip or in the oral cavity consistent with oral cancer, or</li><li>A red or red and white patch in the oral cavity consistent with erythroplakia or erythroleukoplakia (new NICE recommendation for 2015).</li></ul></li></ul></li><li>Thyroid cancer<ul><li>Over 2500 new thyroid cancers are diagnosed each year in the UK.</li><li>It is seen in both sexes. Approximately 70% of new diagnoses are in females.</li><li>The 5 year survival is over 90%.</li><li>Thyroid cancer usually presents as a nodule within the thyroid gland, or as diffuse thyroid swelling. The cancer may also present with regional lymphadenopathy.</li><li>Consider a suspected cancer pathway referral (for an appointment within 2 weeks) for thyroid cancer in people with an unexplained thyroid lump (new NICE recommendation for 2015).</li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field fdfbbc09-6778-4d34-9a50-eda98b4694c4 --><!-- end item 35f5c36d-823e-45fb-a6e9-8faa517317ae -->","topic":{"id":"d8aeca55-824e-5d14-99a2-03d75201d424","topicId":"31afbe15-278a-4fa5-9176-8037cc84e2a6","topicName":"Head and neck cancers - recognition and referral","slug":"head-neck-cancers-recognition-referral","aliases":[],"chapters":[{"id":"5a4e0ab7-b961-5ac5-acf5-588f3e0eb657","slug":"summary","fullItemName":"Summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"e2ed77e5-6a49-52b3-a7fd-bdd665b1ac76","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","subChapters":[]},{"id":"ba35a98e-d808-5721-832f-61561bd61a4e","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","subChapters":[{"id":"34efa250-8c4b-51c0-a8d7-495cb8e50c94","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"1bb4a581-7036-5e5c-9166-7d3b82ddfbf4","slug":"update","fullIte